Interface Multimap<K,V>

Type Parameters:
K - the type of keys maintained by this multimap
V - the type of mapped values
All Known Subinterfaces:
ListMultimap<K,V>, SetMultimap<K,V>, SortedSetMultimap<K,V>
All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractListMultimap, AbstractMultimap, AbstractSetMultimap, AbstractSortedSetMultimap, ArrayListMultimap, ForwardingMultimap, HashMultimap, LinkedHashMultimap, LinkedListMultimap, TreeMultimap
public interface Multimap<K,V>

A collection similar to a Map, but which may associate multiple values with a single key. If you call put(K, V) twice, with the same key but different values, the multimap contains mappings from the key to both values.

The methods get(K), keySet(), keys(), values(), entries(), and asMap() return collections that are views of the multimap. If the multimap is modifable, updating it can change the contents of those collection, and updating those collections will change the multimap. In contrast, replaceValues(K, java.lang.Iterable) and removeAll(java.lang.Object) return collections that are independent of subsequent multimap changes.

Depending on the implementation, a multimap may or may not allow duplicate key-value pairs. In other words, the multimap contents after adding the same key and value twice varies between implementations. In multimaps allowing duplicates, the multimap will contain two mappings, and get will return a collection that includes the value twice. In multimaps not supporting duplicates, the multimap will contain a single mapping from the key to the value, and get will return a collection that includes the value once.

get

Collection<V> get(@Nullable
                  K key)
Returns a collection view of all values associated with a key. If no mappings in the multimap have the provided key, an empty collection is returned.

The returned collection may or may not be modifiable, depending on the implementation. If it allows modifications, changes to it will update the underlying multimap.

Parameters:
key - key to search for in multimap
Returns:
the collection of values that the key maps to

put

boolean put(K key,
            V value)
Stores a key-value pair in the multimap (optional operation).

Some multimap implementations allow duplicate key-value pairs, in which case put always adds a new key-value pair and increases the multimap size by 1. Other implementations prohibit duplicates, and put will replace an existing key-value pair when the keys and values are equal.

Parameters:
key - key to store in the multimap
value - value to store in the multimap
Returns:
true if the method increased the size of the multimap, or false if the multimap already contained the key-value pair and doesn't allow duplicates
Throws:
UnsupportedOperationException - if not supported

putAll

void putAll(@Nullable
            K key,
            Iterable<? extends V> values)
Stores a collection of values with the same key (optional operation).

Some multimap implementations allow duplicate key-value pairs, in which case putAll adds a new key-value pair for each element in values and increases the multimap size by the size of values. Other implementations prohibit duplicates, and putAll will replace an existing key-value pair when the keys and values are equal.

Parameters:
key - key to store in the multimap
values - values to store in the multimap
Throws:
UnsupportedOperationException - if not supported

putAll

void putAll(Multimap<? extends K,? extends V> multimap)
Copies all of another multimap's key-value pairs into this multimap (optional operation). The order in which the mappings are added is determined by multimap.entries().

Some multimap implementations allow duplicate key-value pairs, in which case putAll adds a new key-value pair for each mapping in multimap and increases the multimap size by the size of the supplied multimap. Other implementations prohibit duplicates, and putAll will replace an existing key-value pair when the keys and values are equal.

Parameters:
multimap - mappings to store in this multimap
Throws:
UnsupportedOperationException - if not supported

keys

Multiset<K> keys()
Returns a collection, which may contain duplicates, of all keys. The number of times of key appears in the returned collection equals the number of mappings the key has in the multimap.

The returned multiset may or may not be modifiable, depending on the implementation. If it allows modifications, changes to it will update the underlying multimap.

Returns:
a multiset with keys corresponding to the distinct keys of the multimap and frequencies corresponding to the number of values that each key maps to

entries

Collection<Map.Entry<K,V>> entries()
Returns a collection of all key-value pairs.

The returned collection may or may not be modifiable, depending on the implementation. If it allows modifications, changes to it will update the underlying multimap. The collection supports element removal, which removes the corresponding mapping from the map. It does not support the add or addAll operations.

Returns:
collection of map entries consisting of key-value pairs

collectionEntries

@Deprecated
Set<Map.Entry<K,Collection<V>>> collectionEntries()
Deprecated. Replaced by asMap().entrySet()

Returns a set of map entries, each of which associates a key with its corresponding values in the multimap.

The returned set may or may not be modifiable, depending on the implementation. If it allows modifications, changes to it will update the underlying multimap. The set supports element removal, which removes the corresponding mapping from the map. It does not support the add, addAll or Entry.setValue operations.

If the multimap is modified while an iteration over the set is in progress (except through the iterator's own remove operation) the results of the iteration are undefined.

Returns:
set of map entries, each mapping a key to a collection of values

asMap

Map<K,Collection<V>> asMap()
Returns a map view that associates each key with the corresponding values in the multimap.

The returned map may or may not be modifiable, depending on the implementation. If it allows modifications, changes to it will update the underlying multimap. In particular, the map may support element removal, which removes the corresponding mappings from the multimap. It never supports setValue() on the map entries, put, or putAll.

The collections returned by asMap().get(Object) have the same behavior as those returned by get(K).

Returns:
a map view from a key to its collection of values

equals

boolean equals(@Nullable
               Object other)
Compares the specified object to this multimap for equality. Two multimaps are equal if and only if their map views, as returned by asMap(), are equal.

Note that two multimaps with identical key-value mappings may or may not always be equal, depending on the implementation. For example, SetMultimap equality is independent of ordering, while ListMultimap equality is dependent on the order of values for a given key.

Overrides:
